[{"id":"VR252356","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">This question is a long free-response question. Show your work for each part of the question. (15 points, suggested time 25 minutes)</p>\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram. In the diagram, a vertical support rod is positioned at the center of a circular platform. A string  of length L extends   downward and to the right from the top of the rod, at an angle labeled theta.  A sphere of mass m is attached to the other end of the string. The sphere is shown moving circularly around the vertical rod, as the platform is moving in a counterclockwise fashion.\" height=\"171\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252356.g01.png\" width=\"220\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A vertical support rod is fixed at the center of a platform. A light string of length <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">L</span> is attached to the top of the support rod, and the other end of the string is attached to a sphere of mass <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">m</span>, as shown above. The platform rotates with an angular speed that can be varied. When the platform rotates with a constant angular speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega\"><math alttext=\"omega\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>&nbsp;(omega), the string makes an angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>&nbsp;(theta) with the rod.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two pairs of axes. For both pairs of axes, the horizontal axis is labeled t, the vertical axis is labeled Angular Momentum, and the point where the two axes meet is labeled O. The first pair of axes is labeled Graph A. The graph is a curve that begins at a level point on the vertical axis, just above the origin. It moves to the right gradually curving upward until it levels off at a maximum, high above the horizontal axis. The curve then gradually curves downward until it levels off and ends at the same height that it began. The second pair of axes is labeled Graph B. The graph is a line that begins on the vertical axis, high above the origin, and extends horizontally to the right until it ends.\" height=\"190\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252356.g02.png\" width=\"385\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) The platform rotates with a constant angular speed. Which of the above graphs correctly shows the magnitude of the angular momentum of the platform as a function of time <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">t</span> about a vertical axis at the center of the support rod? Briefly justify your answer.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252356_rubric"},{"id":"VR252356","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) The platform rotates with a constant angular speed. Is the net torque exerted on the platform about its center clockwise, counterclockwise, or zero? Explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252356_rubric"},{"id":"VR252356","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) As the period of rotation becomes very small, what value does <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> approach? Without writing any equations or formulas, justify your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252356_rubric"},{"id":"VR252356","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) A student derives an equation for the square of the period of revolution <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T</span> of the sphere as a function of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta, colon. T squared, equals, open paren, 4 pi squared, close paren. times the fraction with numerator L, cosine theta, and denominator g.\"><math alttext=\"theta, colon. T squared, equals, open paren, 4 pi squared, close paren. times the fraction with numerator L, cosine theta, and denominator g.\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mrow><mo>:</mo></mrow></mstyle><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><msup><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>π</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo></mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.15em\"></mspace><mi>cos</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Indicate whether the equation is consistent with your answer in part (c) and explain why.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252356_rubric"},{"id":"VR252356","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:E part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"E\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) In a series of experimental trials, a group of students changes <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">L</span> and adjusts <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T</span> to keep <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> constant. They record <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">L</span> and <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">T</span> for each trial. If the students use the equation given in part (d), what quantities could they graph to yield a straight line whose slope could be used to find the acceleration due to gravity, <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">g </span>?</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252356_rubric"},{"id":"VR252356","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:F part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"F\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(f) As the angular speed of the platform increases, does the period of revolution of the sphere increase, decrease, or stay the same? Briefly explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252356_rubric"}]